</ul>
<p><a name="Notes" id="Notes"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Phase-shift_keying&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Notes</span></h2>
<div class="references-small">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-ref80211-0">^ <a href="#cite_ref-ref80211_0-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-ref80211_0-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="http://standards.ieee.org/getieee802/download/802.11-1999.pdf" class="external text" title="http://standards.ieee.org/getieee802/download/802.11-1999.pdf" rel="nofollow">IEEE Std 802.11-1999: Wireless LAN Medium Access Control (MAC) and Physical Layer (PHY) Specifications</a> — the overarching IEEE 802.11 specification.</li>
<li id="cite_note-80211b-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-80211b_1-0" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://standards.ieee.org/getieee802/download/802.11b-1999.pdf" class="external text" title="http://standards.ieee.org/getieee802/download/802.11b-1999.pdf" rel="nofollow">IEEE Std 802.11b-1999 (R2003)</a> — the IEEE 802.11b specification.</li>
<li id="cite_note-80211g-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-80211g_2-0" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://standards.ieee.org/getieee802/download/802.11g-2003.pdf" class="external text" title="http://standards.ieee.org/getieee802/download/802.11g-2003.pdf" rel="nofollow">IEEE Std 802.11g-2003</a> — the IEEE 802.11g specification.</li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.atmel.com/dyn/resources/prod_documents/doc2056.pdf" class="external free" title="http://www.atmel.com/dyn/resources/prod_documents/doc2056.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.atmel.com/dyn/resources/prod_documents/doc2056.pdf</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4" title="">^</a></b> Communications Systems, H. Stern &amp; S. Mahmoud, Pearson Prentice Hall, 2004, p283</li>
<li id="cite_note-5"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5" title="">^</a></b> Although the concept of 4-QAM and QPSK are different, the resulting modulation schemes are the same.</li>
</ol>
</div>
